<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="721" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[149,1127,1439,1623]" pageId="6" pageNumber="721">
Body length 3.2 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[622,635,1439,1463]" pageId="6" pageNumber="721">–</emphasis>
5.0 mm. Body completely orange.Antennomere III about 1.3–1.5 times longer than anntenomere II. Pronotum transverse, 1.6 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[984,997,1471,1495]" pageId="6" pageNumber="721">–</emphasis>
2.2 times as wide as long, covered with fine dense punctures. Elytra glabrous. Aedeagus relatively short, simple (
<figureCitation box="[237,317,1535,1559]" captionStart="Figs 66–69" captionStartId="26.[151,188,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[216,1055,416,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-45@26.[207,1071,413,1499]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 66–69.Aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view; ventral view). 66 – Hesperopenna vietnamica (Medvedev, 2000) (paratype); 67 – H. antennalis (Kimoto, 1989); 68 – H. minor (Kimoto, 1989) (paratype); 69 – H. bicolor (Kimoto, 1989) (paratype). Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740073" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740073/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="721">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
